<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1993 (19): Banks slower
to catch on - Applications debate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSIDERING banks have always been among the leading exploiters of
computing, they have come quite late into electronic data interchange (EDI).
While the likes of Tesco were starting to trade electronically in 1987, the
first EDI banking services were not launched until Barclays and National
Westminster entered the market in 1990.
This business is growing rather slowly, not least because some of the early
users of EDI, notably retail chains, are balking at the cost. One suggestion
is that the turmoil in the banking market in recent years has made the banks
desperate to find new ways to make profit and they see EDI as a golden
opportunity.
Tesco director Mr Dave MacInnis sums up the view of many business customers:
'The whole idea of paperless trading through EDI is that it cuts
administrative costs. Yet these bank services want to charge four times what
it costs to process a cheque.
'We regard that as excessive and we are somewhat in dispute with the banks.
It's a shame, because we have electronic trading throughout the business
chain but at the end of the process we still have to produce a piece of
paper, a cheque.'
A measure of the gap between the retail chains and the banks is the reply
from Mr Saif Rahman, business development manager at National Westminster
responsible for EDI services: 'Four times the cheque-processing cost? I say
that is very cheap, considering the services we are offering.'
NatWest's Bankline Interchange service was developed on an IBM AS/400
computer by Terence Chapman Associates, a London consultancy and systems
house, at a cost of Pounds 1.8m. The system is linked to all the main UK EDI
services, run by INS, AT&amp;T-Istel, IBM and British Telecom, so that companies
exchanging orders and invoices by EDI can complete the trading circle by
making payments and notifying the recipients electronically, too.
The service offers prompt payment, the provision of information such as
remittance advices to recipients and facilities such as the ability to sign
off batches of payments but assign different settlement dates to each item.
Saif Rahman says the service combines the good points of the BACS national
payments clearing service and of traditional cheques.
'We offer the speed of BACS and the control and information provided by
cheques,' he says.
'BACS is not the system for complex payments: the amount of information you
can provide is limited, so you can't include details such as discounts,
invoice numbers and so on.
'If you send magnetic tapes of payment details by courier to BACS, you get
an acknowledgement by post, so there is some time before you know the
transactions have been received and are being processed.
'With an EDI service, the network itself confirms the time it received a
message and the time it was looked at by the recipient.'
Saif Rahman's views on BACS are backed by Food Brokers, a middleman between
the grocery and pharmaceutical trades and retail groups, including Tesco.
'We've tended to shy away from BACS, even though it gives us cleared funds,
because we lose a bit of control,' says Mr Duncan Knight, Food Brokers'
administration manager. 'We actually prefer to collect payment ourselves and
key in the information in the way we want.
'Our payment terms are 30 days, so if a cheque hasn't arrived after that
time, we can chase it the next day. If payments are made by BACS, it can be
two or three days after the customer has sent the tape to BACS before you
know whether you've been paid.
'You have to check with the bank and they have to make their own checks, so
you're backwards and forwards with phone calls.'
Saif Rahman at NatWest says the main benefits of bank EDI services are
prompt payment, which enables companies to negotiate discounts with their
suppliers, and control and efficiency through the information provided by
the service.
HE believes the discounts argument is one reason why retail chains in
particular have not rushed to sign up for the services: the huge numbers of
low-value items passing very quickly through supermarkets already enable big
retailers to negotiate good discounts.
Even so, he believes the likes of Tesco are wrong in comparing the cost of a
BACS payment or of a cheque and a postage stamp with the cost of a bank EDI
service.
'The banks charge roughly Pounds 1 for a payment and a remittance advice
with their EDI services,' Mr Rahman says. 'Research by the Inter-Bank
Research Organisation and others shows that the cost of producing a cheque
and sending it with a remittance advice starts at Pounds 1.60.
'It's not just an 18p stamp - there's a time-cost, the cost of the cheques,
probably specially printed with the company logo, the cost of keeping the
cheques secure . . . and so on.'
For retailing and product manufacturing applications, see pages 14-16
</TEXT>
