<PROFILE>_AN-DCKCYAGRFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930311
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1993 (18): Early fears
give way to enthusiasm - A long-established family business in Scotland
discovers the benefits of trading electronically / Case study of Product
supplier - Thomas Tunnock
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BAKER and confectionery manufacturer Thomas Tunnock says it was pushed into
electronic data interchange (EDI) by Tesco, the food retailer - but a year
later it is more than satisfied with the result.
Tunnock's, as the company is known, has been baking in Uddington, on the
outskirts of Glasgow, for more than 100 years. Today this family business
has a Pounds 25m turnover and 700 staff; its biscuits, chocolate and caramel
wafers, tea cakes and marshmallow Snowballs are exported to more than 30
countries.
Tunnock's moved into computing in a big way in 1990, replacing its
accounting package with a total financial, sales, production and materials
management system from Trifid Software and installing a bigger computer from
McDonnell Douglas Information Systems.
The system is accessed by 30 terminals and personal computers, including
three in the London office, which previously sent orders to the head office
by post.
Soon after the Trifid system went live, Tunnock's found Tesco promoting EDI.
'Tesco wanted us to use its package, sent us details of the product,
training, costs and so on,' says computer systems manager Mr Joe Hailey.
'No one here knew anything about EDI, so we held back until we'd looked into
it.
'Tesco never said we had to go EDI or else, but we got the impression that
if we didn't we would have no more business from them.'
Mr Hailey says its big retail chain customers were very helpful in getting
Tunnock's into EDI and that the whole operation 'went very smoothly.'
Tunnock's settled on an EDI software package from Trifid's sister company,
Kewill Xetal. It costs around Pounds 900. This package provides access to
all EDI services, an important consideration for Tunnock's, because another
big customer, Safeway, uses the IBM EDI network rather than the INS Tradanet
service favoured by Tesco.
Tunnock's uses a personal computer to link to Tradanet: this is the cheapest
way of connecting, because INS bases its charges on the size of the trader's
computer. So another package, a Pounds 250 product from Pixel Innovations,
has been added to convert the EDI messages into the format the Trifid system
can understand and vice versa.
IT cost Tunnock's Pounds 5,200 to join the Tradanet service, including the
necessary software, training and consultancy, so the total set-up cost,
including the Kewill Xetal and Pixel packages, was around Pounds 6,350.
There is now a monthly charge to INS of just over Pounds 80, or Pounds 975 a
year. So far, Tunnock's only uses EDI to receive orders and this is free on
Tradanet, although there is a storage charge if messages are not removed
after seven days.
Tunnock's now trades electronically with Tesco, ASDA, Sainsbury and Safeway
and sees clear benefits.
'Orders come in by EDI and pass into the Trifid system, so details are
available in minutes to everyone in the organisation: for example, to senior
executives for management information and to production people,' Joe Hailey
says.
'The more companies we trade with electronically, the greater the benefits
of EDI.
'We pride ourselves on the fact that we make to order, so our products are
always fresh. Now, as more and more companies send us orders via EDI
directly into the Trifid system, we can set up longer production runs,
handling two or three orders at a time.
'With EDI and the Trifid business system, orders sent by our customers on
Monday can be scheduled for production on Wednesday and delivered on
Thursday. Previously, orders might come through the post from the London
office and someone might spend an hour a day keying the information in from
documents that had already been produced by hand. This slowed our response
to orders and was naturally error-prone.'
Joe Hailey says around 50 of Tunnock's 300 or more customers are probably of
suitable size and computing sophistication to trade electronically.
EDI could also be used to trade with a dozen or so suppliers. These
suppliers include giant groups in the sugar and chocolate business. However,
Tunnock's is working initially with its main packaging supplier here: an
Edinburgh company, William Thyne. The project is William Thyne's first move
into EDI.
'We're not pushing them into it,' says Mr Hailey.
'They were keen to pursue it and we are their ideal EDI partner, as one of
their biggest customers.'
Meanwhile Tunnock's is expanding its EDI relationship with some of its
customers.
'Tesco is talking to us about sending us sales forecasts,' says Mr Hailey.
'This will be useful for our production people especially.'
From being a rather anxious newcomer to EDI, Tunnock's has become something
of an enthusiastic user and keen to exploit it in different ways.
'The fact that we're into EDI will make a difference for our sales manager
when he's talking to new customers,' says Joe Hailey.
'We can be up-and-running in days and then we can process orders quickly and
there's no danger of orders going missing.
'Initially, when we only had EDI links to one customer, we weren't certain
about the benefits. But EDI is certainly paying for itself now.'
A boon for small businesses: see page 20
