<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1993 (17): Supermarket
pioneer / Here and on the following pages, John Kavanagh examines electronic
trading from the different perspectives of customers and suppliers in the
EDI chain - and uncovers the benefits and problems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHECK-OUT operators in a Tesco food supermarket are the only human link in
the entire business chain of recording sales, amending and checking stock
records, re-ordering goods, receiving and checking invoices and making
payment.
All these actions are handled entirely automatically and are sparked off by
sales recorded at the check-out point.
Tesco has been a pioneer in electronic data interchange (EDI) and heads the
biggest retail EDI community outside the US. Over 1,200 suppliers, supplying
more than 95 per cent of the products on Tesco supermarket shelves, now
trade electronically with the company.
Almost half these suppliers send their invoices to Tesco by EDI. And a
quarter have an even closer relationship, receiving 13-week sales forecasts
through the EDI network.
Tesco has been using the INS Tradanet EDI service since 1987. During that
time it has also installed barcode scanners at most of its 400-odd
supermarkets.
This combination of EDI and scanning has enabled it to automate its trading
from end to end.
The check-out terminal records sales of individual items. Every evening
Tesco's central mainframe computer system connects automatically to each
supermarket computer to retrieve that sales data.
The data brings stock files up to date and the new levels determine whether
orders should be placed and the size of those orders. The orders are sent
through the EDI service to suppliers, many of which can send ba ck their
invoices by EDI. The Tesco systems can then produce cheques from the
invoices. These payments, too, could be made automatically through EDI if
Tesco and other retail chains could come to agreement with the banks (see
applications debate, page 18).
All this happens without any human involvement. The benefits have been so
great that Tesco has given up measuring them - 'benefits? You name it,' says
stock management director Mr Dave MacInnis. 'We know for certain that we've
reduced stock levels yet improved stock availability and sales, cut lead
times on orders, cut administration, improved communications with our
suppliers. It's not just EDI that has brought the benefits - it's all bound
up with other developments such as barcode scanning - but EDI has been very
much the enabling tool.'
The benefits are so great that the costs of running EDI through the Tradanet
service are 'absolutely negligible,' Mr MacInnis says: 'The basic running
costs are covered by our savings on use of the phone, fax and mail. That
means we have achieved all the business benefits for nothing.'
EDI and scanning have also enabled Tesco to re-organise its distribution, to
the benefit of itself and its suppliers. Deliveries from suppliers now go to
eight warehouses instead of directly to the supermarkets. The precise sales
data gathered each night allows orders to be placed on the warehouses as
close as possible to the time the goods will be sold.
This means the supermarkets only need hold minimal stocks, so they can
devote more space to sales. The number of deliveries is reduced to a
minimum, as all goods come from one Tesco warehouse rather than from
separate suppliers. And all checking of the quality and quantities delivered
by suppliers is done at the warehouses rather than at individual stores.
The suppliers benefit by receiving just one order for each warehouse, rather
than separate orders from hundreds of stores.
Similarly, they only deliver to the warehouses. The savings in their
distribution costs give Tesco the opportunity to negotiate better terms.
Dave MacInnis reacts sharply to suggestions that Tesco enjoys such benefits
from EDI that it has threatened to cut off suppliers which do not sign up.
'We see EDI as a cornerstone in the effective management of our supply chain
and those of our suppliers,' he says. 'Our insistence might sometimes come
across as bullying, but where do you draw the line between that and saying
this is the way we see business going: towards greater efficiency and the
elimination of paperwork.'
He adds: 'The success of our approach is shown by the fact that we have not
de-listed a single supplier or threatened to do so. In a recession some
companies are reluctant to invest in a new broom, let alone something like
EDI. Yet we've got hundreds of companies which are saving money on
traditionally paper-bound activities such as order processing and
invoicing.'
Around 200 suppliers have yet to sign up for EDI, although most are
companies supplying specialist products or services in low volumes, such as
fascias for stores. Tesco helps companies get going, not least through a
Tesco account team at INS. Dave MacInnis says it takes about six weeks from
an initial meeting to get a company 'going live.'
TESCO has now started communicating with individuals in its supplier
companies through INS' electronic mail service. There are 4,000 electronic
mail users in Tesco and they can communicate with 3,000 contacts in 200
suppliers.
Dave MacInnis points to the benefits of electronic mail, such as the ability
to send reports and memos directly from personal computers and the
elimination of problems in trying to telephone an elusive business contact.
Tesco is also providing sales forecasts via EDI to over 280 suppliers. It
works on sales history data, seasonal factors, local knowledge, planned
promotions, load sizes and so on to produce forecasts of up to 13 weeks by
product and by warehouse. This helps suppliers schedule production and
reduce their own stocks and lead times.
Tesco's exploitation of EDI certainly adds a new significance to that can of
baked beans about to pass through the check-out.
The EDI chain: see page 15
</TEXT>
