<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1993 (16): Investment
pays dividends, say users - Britain leads the way in Europe in applying
electronic data interchange services, although it is still early days for
the concept.  Now EDI suppliers are seeking to attract thousands of small
company users / Suppliers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SUPPLIERS of electronic data interchange (EDI) services are far from
satisfied with UK market growth which the research company Input says is
running at over 25 per cent a year, writes John Kavanagh.
Market leader INS has already slashed its prices this year, following price
changes by competitors in 1992. Newcomer British Telecom still negotiates
each contract individually and is 'doing some good deals,' according to
users. It expects to publish a standard price list this spring.
'EDI penetration in the UK is still only five per cent,' says Mr Neil
Lawrence, EDI commercial manager at BT. 'Only 300 of the Times top 1,000 use
it, although there is a lot of interest during the recession, because it
cuts costs.
'We expect the number of top 1,000 companies using EDI to double in the next
two or three years - and each big company brings in another 2,000 or more of
its suppliers.'
INS is going directly for those smaller companies with its price cuts.
'We signed more than 1,100 companies last year, almost a quarter of our
total, but there is more serious competition now and we want to stimulate
growth still further,' says INS managing director Mr Lee Tate. 'Big growth
will only continue if we attract the thousands and thousands of small
companies.'
INS, jointly owned by ICL and international EDI service company GEIS, was
set up in 1985 to launch the Tradanet service, defined by the Article Number
Association, for retailers and their suppliers. It claims to have 55 per
cent of the UK market from this and other EDI communities. Around 6m
documents pass through its network each month.
INS' traditional rival has been AT&amp;T-Istel. Then come IBM, GEIS and, since
October 1991, BT.
In Europe as a whole, research analysts at IDC estimate INS and GEIS equal
with 33 per cent, IBM with 13 per cent and AT&amp;T with nine per cent.
There are links between the services: an early complaint about INS and
AT&amp;T-Istel was that users had to connect to both networks to trade
electronically with all their customers. However, this was no longer an
issue for companies interviewed by Software At Work. Even smaller companies
trading with customers on different networks preferred to have separate
connections to each network.
'Interconnectivity is a lot more than just communications links,' says Mr
David Elliott, EDI manager at British Gas. 'When you link to one service,
you have a complete audit trail: you know your message arrived and when
someone looked at it. I'd rather pay for the link direct to the separate
services than use the bridges between them.'
Several users made similar comments, pointing to possible problems of
sorting out legal responsibility if a message got lost.
As well as network providers, the EDI market also includes companies
providing software for linking to the various networks and converting data
into and out of the correct message formats.
Input says network services currently account for just over 60 per cent of
the European market, software for 16 per cent and consultancy for 23 per
cent. It expects network services to grow to 72 per cent by 1997, at the
expense of consultancy.
Charging structures vary from one network supplier to the next. There is
generally a one-off joining fee of Pounds 200-Pounds 250 for a personal
computer link.
After that, comparisons are difficult: software for handling links to one or
more services can cost up to Pounds 2,750 for a personal computer or between
Pounds 1,500 and Pounds 55,000 for a mainframe, depending on the facilities
required.
Some suppliers make a monthly charge (INS' is Pounds 50) which includes free
receipt of any amount of data and a small charge for sending it; others have
no monthly fee but charge for both sending and receiving. This means charges
per 1,000 characters can range from 2.5p to 10p.
After all the complicated pricing formulae have been compared, personal
computer users will find EDI will probably cost them a few hundred pounds a
year. Mainframe users will pay considerably more: IBM says Pounds 10,000 is
a typical running cost for the first year alone, when a company is likely to
have only a few EDI partners.
However, all users, of varying sizes and usage, contacted by Software At
Work felt their initial investment and running costs were paying dividends.
</TEXT>
<XX>
