<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1993 (15): How to save
time, effort and money - EDI is a simple idea with big business implications
/ Analysis
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ELECTRONIC data interchange (EDI) is a simple idea which both users and
service suppliers see as a direct path to the goals of just-in-time trading
and business re-organisation.
On the surface it is simply the exchange of routine business documents such
as orders, acknowledgements and invoices between computers run by suppliers
and their customers.
This itself is enough of a justification for companies to move into EDI, as
the case studies in the following pages show.
It has been estimated that 50-70 per cent of all computer output becomes
computer input. Without EDI, information is keyed into one computer, printed
as an order, posted to a supplier and keyed in again. And this process is
repeated down the supply chain.
At each stage there are delays as documents go through the post, get passed
between departments and are keyed in. The greater the human involvement, the
greater the risk of error: research shows that 15 per cent of the value of
invoices raised in the UK is lost because of errors or misplaced documents.
EDI can remove all human involvement and transfer documents in seconds.
Tesco has automated its business chain to such an extent that orders,
invoices and payments are all triggered off by shoppers passing through
supermarket check-outs - and there is no other human involvement at all in
the entire chain.
There are clear benefits here from the elimination of paperwork. In
addition, the huge cuts in the time between identifying a need for more
stocks and getting an order processed and delivered have paved the way for
just-in-time ordering and manufacturing.
This, in turn, is leading the EDI pioneers into closer partnerships with
their suppliers, in some cases invoicing themselves for goods received and
providing information such as sales forecasts. At the same time, EDI is
adding an extra dimension to price negotiations, with customers arguing for
bigger discounts because their suppliers are saving money with EDI and
getting prompt payment through EDI banking services.
'EDI presents the opportunity to modify the relationship between business
partners which recognise their mutual dependence and endeavour to build on
it together for greater success,' says EDI consultant Mr Jon Sasserath of
computing services group CMG.
As with the early days of the fax machine (and, indeed, the telephone), the
extent to which the benefits outweigh the costs depends on the number of
partners that a company can trade with electronically. EDI is used by only
around five per cent of companies in the UK, which is far ahead of all other
European countries.
This issue is summed up by Mr Martyn Daniels, systems strategy controller at
the B&amp;Q DIY chain and chairman of the user group for the Tradanet EDI
service: 'We don't want to have to run two finance departments and two
logistics departments, one manual and the other electronic.'
This understandable attitude has led to accusations that big companies have
pushed their suppliers into EDI with threats of cutting off their business.
Two medium-sized suppliers to big groups, interviewed for this survey, both
used almost exactly the same words when asked about justifying the costs -
'we didn't need a cost-justification, because the cost of not going EDI
would have been no more business.'
However, these and all the other companies interviewed were well-satisfied
with EDI and looking to expand their use, both in their relationships with
their major customers and in trading with their own suppliers.
Mr David Andrews, head of the Andersen Consulting's Financial Services
Division, looks at the influence of the big companies from another angle. He
argues that each big trading community needs a controlling body or sponsor.
Without it, there is a danger that the EDI service company can be in charge,
locking trading partners in, he says.
David Andrews points to cases such as that of Tesco, where a big customer
leads the development and helps its smaller trading partners, and to other
areas where rival companies have got together to set up a trading community
through a single EDI service supplier which they monitor through a
management committee (there are examples of such communities in the
following pages).
All the companies interviewed by Soft
ware At Work found the move into EDI was fairly straightforward technically.
Service suppliers, software companies and even the big EDI trading partners
offer software packages which handle links into the different services and
the conversion of data from business systems into the correct message format
standards.
Users seem unconcerned about the fact that different industries and groups
of users follow different standards. There is a general gradual move to the
international Edifact standard but the various EDI services already provide
conversion from one standard to another if required, so users see themselves
little affected. As Jon Sasserath at CMG puts it: 'Implementing the
technology is a piece of cake, especially when compared with defining,
planning and implementing the strategic business move that EDI should
represent.'
David Andrews at Andersen Consulting agrees: 'Businesses need to aim for a
more efficient processes, a whole step change. This goes well beyond EDI,
which is not a solution but a very important tool.'
And Mr Sasserath concludes: 'EDI is the way forward. The future prosperity,
even survival, of a business may depend on implementing it successfully. EDI
may be inflicted on companies or it may be a mutual decision. But the old
adage still applies: there will be those who make it happen, those who let
it happen - and those who wondered what the hell happened.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
