<DOCNO>FT931-4273</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DCKCYAGMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930311
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1993 (13): Substantial
business benefits for BT - How software helps track complex projects and
reduce operational costs / Large scale application
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN a company the size of British Telecom, with annual capital investment of
Pounds 2.5bn, an efficient project management system is vital. BT Worldwide
Networks had long experience of various software packages for project
management because efficiency in that area is so central to its business.
(BT is famous for having 'one of everything' on the software market, to keep
abreast of new technology). Nevertheless, BTWN wanted to simplify the
situation and reduce operational costs by fixing on one package.
It comes as a surprise that, when standardising on a country-wide system for
its project management, BT picked a little-known system, Hornet. It comes
from a small software house, Claremont Controls, based in Morpeth in the
North East, (see details, page 14). When BT took delivery of Hornet XT last
April, it became Claremont's premier customer, and something of a pioneer
with the software.
BT's entire business is dependent on technology (see company snapshot,
facing page). It is constantly installing new exchanges and updating older
equipment on a country-wide basis. As might be expected, there were a number
of methods being used to keep track of projects, including paper and a
variety of software tools.
BT is constantly working on a large scale. Where there were 60 areas ten
years ago (and relatively little PM computerisation), there are now eight
zones, plus London. Any one zone might have 15,000 jobs running
concurrently. The tendency to take a wider, 'macro level' view makes
information flow vital to managers, according to Bob Martin Royle, who heads
the Wasp/Hornet programme.
'The senior field planning managers need visibility across a wider and wider
area, with efficient support tools to enable them to plan, monitor and
control their capital works programmes. The whole point is to manage our
capital investment programme more efficiently.'
IN 30 years he has seen the evolution of paper-based systems and the rise of
computer-based project management, and is familiar with products such as
Artemis and SuperProject, which were already in use at BT.
With 400 full-time project managers across the country, standardisation
became important - 'there are significant business benefits in getting our
own systems standardised,' explains BT implementation manager Martin Baker.
'Once we've chosen tools, we can work on standardising practives and
procedures which improve control of the investment programme, to such a
degree that clients will notice improved efficiency.' Although BT uses IBM
mainframes to run its telephone exchange administration, it has an open
systems development policy for in-house work, and runs a number of
Unix-based minicomputers. There was not a wide selection of project
management systems available under Unix, and a further requirement, that of
interfacing with the Informix database, narrowed the field even further.
The Informix integration was important because BT Worldwide Networks had
already invested a great deal in building an Informix-based system,
co-incidentally called Wasp - the Works And Stores Programme - which stores
all the details of various jobs under way. The plan was to link Wasp and
Hornet to BT's own standards. Choosing the Hornet system was only the start
of the story.
The introduction, user consultation, and user sampling of Hornet has itself
been the subject of a large in-house project. To implement the system, BT
Group Computing Services has had to design and provide a national data
communications network to accommodate an additional 3,300 users. BTWN
started its own training programme for an eventual 4,000 users.
THE problem with which users have to deal on a day-to-day basis, as
Martin-Royle points out, is that change is the only constant. However
well-planned the existing timetable of works, there are always new and
changing requirements, 'injected works' which alter the picture - 'we're in
a competitive environment and have to respond to new needs, and with them
the 'what if?' scenario, all the time.'
He describes his role as very much the user's champion, and his working
party, when defining its standard system, had well-defined wish list. They
wanted a user friendly system, compatible with other BT systems, which would
allow direct data transfer when ordering stores and allocating resources,
with the ability to give a clear screen-based overview of the work
programmes and how they impacted one another.
Critical path analysis, 'what if' facilities, electronic mail and automatic
report production were vital. Hornet, he believes, fitted the current 'best
practice.'
Martin-Royle, Martin Baker, and project manager Doug Turner are in clear
agreement that at some point, requirements have to be 'frozen,' and the
potential 'jam tomorrow' of newer, promised products abandoned in favour of
something that works here and now. On the ground level, every job BT does
has to be planned, and resources allocated in a strict order. Tactical
planning is the term it uses for the process of identifying the
requirements, and deciding on the best option, for example, installing
additional exchange switching equipment.
The next phase is the traditional 'works planning,' which provides a
detailed forecast of the materials and resources necessary for each job.
This might include a site survey, measurement of cable runs, breakdown of
materials, and cost estimates. Hornet's role is to support the programme and
project levels, producing a schedule of jobs. Wasp is used to track the
actual execution of jobs against the scheduled dates. BT had evolved Wasp,
its works database for all Worldwide Networks internal jobs, out of a
previous Internal Works Info System, IWIS. Used together, the two allow for
cradle-to-grave planning of activities, down to the level of individuals
being allotted to specific tasks at given sites and times. Projects and
injected work requests are logged on to Hornet at the tactical planning
stage, and assessed for the timescale in which they can be achieved. Hornet
helps plan and delivery, through gaining financial authority for the spend,
down to detailed planning, cost estimation, and stores ordering.
It also monitors the job progress, jeopardy, and completion. The 'jeopardy'
part is one of the greatest benefits, as it allows managers to see much
earlier when a job is in danger of running late, or going over budget.
Another advantage is that it is much easier, with systematically stored
information, to see what jobs have in common.
'One installation of an exchange will be very like another in certain
respects,' explains Doug Turner. 'Process management enables us to define a
'template' of a particular sort of job.'
He is rolling the project out in phases over a two-year period with
'facilitators' running workshops and spreading the word. Due to the careful
selection process, in which he says everyone had a voice, there is quite a
demand for the system - 'the problem is to stop people leaping ahead and
asking for more before it's implemented,' he says.
One development he has noted is that managers using the system have begun to
discuss their jobs they with a peer group, and compare performance. It would
be strange if BT, or all organisations, were not to realise the potential of
electronic mail and 'automatic' communications, and this is integral in
Hornet's works.
'If the date for something changes, the scheduling facility send automatic
messages,' says Martin Baker. More than 10 per cent of the mail comes from
outside BT, through 'closed user groups,' including suppliers.
John Smith, based in Leeds, is one of the pilot users of Hornet/Wasp. He is
the manager of field programme control for the north-east zone, stretching
from the Pennines to the east coast, and from Lincolnshire up to the Scots
border.
'We use the scheduling capabilities of Hornet all the time to tell us
whether the work is achievable,' he says. Six people are constantly using
the system, which, he says, improves all the time as they become familiar
with it - 'it's telling us when deadlines aren't likely to be met. Now, we
get the opportunity to be pro-active, rather than reactive.'
*****
COMPANY SNAPSHOT
British Telecom
BT was for many years the UK's only supplier of telecommunications. Its
capital investment of nearly Pounds 2.5bn in 1992 goes into the building and
continual modernisation of its telecommunications network.
BT's investment in network architecture and system design is 'invisible'
compared to large construction projects such as Canary Wharf or Euro-Tunnel,
but involves all the usual project management problems of realising projects
within time, cost and quality parameters. These are increasingly important
now that BT works in a competitive environment.
Turnover: Pounds 13.3bn with Pounds 3bn pre-tax profit in 1992.
Employees: 165,000. Key personnel involved with information technology: Bob
Martin-Royle head of interconnect and emergency planning worldwide networks,
Doug Turner, manager of WASP/Hornet project, Martin Baker implementation
manager.
*****
TECHNOLOGY FILE:
Hardware: Network of eight Pyramid MIServer T series minicomputer.
Software: Hornet is a project management system written to use the Informix
database. The Hornet XK at BT works directly with Informix SQL Online
relational database, communicating directly with Wasp, an in-house BT
developed Informix database. Integration with BT CMS stores database is
under way.
Suppliers: see details below. Other systems used: the Pyramids also host a
Uniplex office automation package, and Wasp Hornet local databases.
Total software costs: in the region of Pounds 250,000, including training
and consultancy.
Installation: Hornet was first installed Spring 1992, rolled out during
1992; full implementation is planned for April, 1993.
*****
SOFTWARE SUPPLIER:
Claremont Controls, a privately owned UK company, founded in 1980. Turnover
is in the region of Pounds 900,000. There are 15 employees.
Product: Hornet XK, a multi-user, multi-level project management system,
which sits directly on top of industry-standard SQL databases including
Ingres, Informix, Ingres, Oracle and Progress. Originally launched in August
1990, the current release is Hornet XK v2.1.1.
Number of users: 500 at 30 sites, all but three in the UK.
Price: Pounds 5,500 starting price for Intel-based system.
Hardware/ operating systems: any Unix system, currently Intel, Sun, Pyramid,
Sequent, IBM RS6000 and Amdahl.
Sales and support: direct from authors, with maintenance at 15 per cent of
purchase price. Other services include installation, training and
consultancy.
User views: 'Flexibility . . . variety of hardware hosts.'
Contact: Mike Phillipson, Claremont Controls, Albert House, Rothbury,
Morpeth, Northumberland; tel 0669 21182.
