<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1993 (11): Topics in the
next issue - Software at Work / Readers' response to 'feedback survey'
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THIS issue of Software At Work deals with two main subjects: project
management (PM) and electronic data interchange, EDI. These two 'user
topics,' topped the voting list of topics in our recent 'feedback' report
from readers. As a result, we have held over our third topic - rapid
application development - until our summer issue in June.
We have taken note of your preferences, and covered both PM and EDI
extensively in this issue, as well as replacing Desktop publishing with
Teleworking as a topic for our next issue. We would also wish to thank
readers who took the trouble to reply to the Feedback Survey, as the votes
have given us valuable guidance. Replies are still coming in, following our
winter issue, (December 6, 1992). We intend to do a full analysis, and
report on the full results.
The next issue of Software At Work in June will look at:
Teleworking (see details, right).
Facilities Management and outsourcing.
Rapid Applications Development, (held over from the March issue).
Teleworking has appeared on the agenda of many companies wishing to cut down
office overheads, and make staff in the field more effective. The increasing
power of laptop and personal computers has been accompanied by software
which has become easier to use, and therefore more practical for 'sit-alone'
users. We are looking for stories which demonstrate positive business
benefits in teleworking.
Facilities management deals with another move outside, as large
computer-users divest themselves of in-house IT operations. Companies are
contracting-out to FM specialists with the aim of concentrating on the core
business.
The first two 'user' topics, follow the usual pattern of interviewing users
of various products and services.
Users and suppliers wishing to participate in the survey should contact
Software At Work at the following address, stating which topic is of
interest and requesting the relevant forms.
Write to: Software and Work, Surveys Secretary, Financial Times, Number One
Southwark Bridge, London, SE1 9HL
