<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1993 (10): New way of
managing skills and resources / Case study of Rockwell Graphics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE paper you're reading
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
at least in the UK edition - was printed on a press made by Rockwell Graphic
Systems, a leading manufacturer of printing presses for newspapers.
Every printing press is slightly different, and every customised delivery
involves the scheduling of a variety of skills and resources as the press is
commissioned. Sometimes this happens on the other side of the world - and to
co-ordinate its resources, Rockwell uses Artemis, the mainframe-based
software from Lucas Management Systems.
When installing outside the UK, Rockwell had felt that the problems of
controlling resources were magnified by distance.
'It was a matter of bringing down the time it takes to install a printing
press and reduce costs, ' explains Maurice Leyland, the manager of
information and material systems.
'We felt we had a problem, but we didn't know what was on the market, and
the first goal was to find out exactly what was needed.'
Decision-making, he admits, was very much by 'gut feel,' using very simple
reports - 'it was a matter of establishing control over an inherently manual
process,' he adds.
With 20 projects annually, and each taking nine months to a year to
complete, the main problem was scheduling scarce resources, such as the
skilled software engineer who set up the presses. The experience of two
full-time project managers, one with an engineering background was a help in
establishing a detailed requirements' analysis.
'It was a focusing exercise. We came up with the need for project management
disciplines,' he adds. The requirements' definition that followed was
derived from establishing the information which Rockwell thought it should
be providing to its customers.
'We wanted graphics to help us demonstrate that we were in full control of
all eventualities in the installation process,' explains Maurice Leyland. 'I
call it the 'gee whizz factor'.'
ROCKWELL wanted a mainframe product, and although it explored several PC
products as well, it found them incapable of managing multiple projects
which all called on the same scarce resources.
Artemis fulfilled the requirements of user-friendliness, and provided the
scheduling facilities Rockwell wanted, as well as needing little extra in
the way of hardware resources, since it fitted on the existing IBM
mainframe.
Rockwell also makes use of a PC tool, Schedule Publisher, which links with
the mainframe. There was also board-level interest in the choice, for the
need for a solution was recognised worldwide. It was also seen as something
that would link with all other Rockwell systems, such as production control
and material requirements' planning.
It would even have a role in the sales function, providing strong control
from the start, so that sales, engineering, manufacturing and customer
services would all work more closely together.
The entire contract was worth Pounds 500,000, split more or less equally
between the cost of the software, and training and consultancy. The software
project is 'owned' by customer services, and the in-house effort to promote
its use is driven by Frank Williams, customer services manager.
Maurice Leyland believes that use of the product has forced some changes for
the better - 'there are a lot of thought processes that have to be changed.
We're going to break down the barriers between different areas of
specialisation. Everything becomes visible.'
However, he offers some valuable advice: 'Beware of the expense. It's a
costly commitment over a long period of time and the expense comes far ahead
of the benefits, The lifespan of a two or three-year order means that the
benefits are not visible straight away.'
*****
SOFTWARE DETAILS
Artemis 9000
This product runs on mainframes, providing comprehensive planning and
control solutions which can be customised to meet specific needs of
different companies.
In addition there is an easy-to-use PC project management tool, Schedule
Publisher.
The Artemis family of products also runs on other systems. It is widely used
in in defence, manufacturing, aerospace, and other industries.
Suppliers: Lucas Management Systems, founded in 1977 in the UK, is a
subsidiary of Lucas Industries. Turnover: more than Pounds 50m in 1991/2.
Number of users: more than 1,000.
Hardware and operating systems: IBM RS6000, ICL DRS6000, HP 9000 300/400,
700/800, DEC system Ultrix, SCO Unix, SUN4, Bull DPX/2, SUN SPARC, IBM
mainframes, and all PC LANS.
Sales and support: direct from Lucas, with full support worldwide,
maintenance cost undisclosed. Other services available: Seminars, training,
technical bulletins.
User views: Pros - 'the number of hardware platforms, ability to allocate
the same resources across different projects, ability to handle large
volumes of data, flexibility, level of support available.'
Cons - 'expensive . . . too grand a scale for smaller requirements.'
Contact: Lucas Management Systems, (London HQ): tel 081 848 3400.
</TEXT>
