<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1993 (5): A finger on the
pulse - Instant analysis, How custom-built software links project
information, including materials and complex labour schedules, into an
accounting system / Case study of The Welding Institute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT IS rare to find an organisation like the Welding Institute which can
justify creating its own custom-built project management system. TWI is
itself one big project, a private limited company and non-profit-making
organisation which specialises in research on welding and joining materials.
It was formed by international collaboration between such manufacturers as
Shell, BA, Jaguar, and the Royal Ordnance. TWI organises between 600 and 700
separate consulting projects annually, including work for international
research projects (Eureka, Esprit) and the Department of Trade and Industry.
Its turnover of Pounds 18m comes largely from project sponsorship, through
its member companies, and partly through fixed-price contracts. Of a staff
of 420, there are over 200 professional scientists, engineers, material
scientists, and mathematicians who are likely to be involved in a number of
projects at any one time, and need to do a great deal of reporting-back.
People who might be world experts in their field are managing four or five
projects at once. The fixed-price nature of the projects makes
time-accounting important, and Ian Smith, commercial manager, makes a useful
between project management and project control.
'It's a matter of size. If one person can keep the whole picture of the
project in his head, and simply need a picture of costs that are mounting
up, that's part of project control. That includes telling the client what
you're doing, proposals, instructions, contracts, costing and estimating,'
says Ian Smith.
'There's a need for weekly feedback on costs, but only one person might know
about technical progress. Project management is what is needed for things
like NASA's space shuttle, which is simply too big for one person to keep
control, or keep tabs on contractors. 'The present batch of products on the
marketplace is really designed for projects such as building the Channel
Tunnel, where the problem is scheduling certain resources at a certain
point, at a particular time.'
In 1990, TWI was unable to find anything ready-made to manage project cash
as well as project scheduling. For smaller project work, individual TWI
researchers use Superproject Expert from Computer Associates. But TWI wanted
something which would link all project-costing information, including
materials, labour and so on, into an accounting system. There was a need to
provide information for use outside TWI as well as inside - 'one of our
functions is to act as a centre for all our members. We're geared up to
showing people exactly what we're doing,' says Ian Smith.
CMG (Computer Management Group) won a competitive tender to provide the CMG:
Fact2000 accounting suite, plus a custom-built project-costing system,
written using the Oracle database. The Project Control and Costing system
feeds information such as purchase orders for materials for a specific
project automatically through to Fact2000. This enables TWI to account by
project.
The system runs on a Prime EXL under SCO Unix, supporting two dozen or so
users, and is also being put onto an IBM PS/2. The entire installation,
including hardware, package, consultancy and the custom-built project
management module, carried a Pounds 100,000 price tag.
It was the analysis of instant information that was lacking from the
Fortran-built database which Mr Smith had previously built for his own
in-house use. This provided a useful prototype in commissioning the CMG
system.
Since its implementation, Mr Smith has written his own little 'management
summary system' using summary reports to analyse various aspects of the
project work. He also makes great use of ad hoc reports, and uses files of
data to analyse further using Lotus 1-2-3.
Choosing a partner was a matter of 'feeling comfortable' with the developer,
says Mr Smith. The system has now become a joint venture between CMG and
TWI, so that TWI receives royalty benefits.
The system has also had wider benefits, he says - 'if you think of
everything as a project, including administrative events like sickness and
holidays, everything becomes easy, because you always have your finger on
the pulse.'
*****
SOFTWARE DETAILS
Project Control and Costing System
This product was a bespoke development for TWI in 1991. Project costs are
monitored against budget for a wide variety of research and development
projects.
The project costs are automatically updated from the input of purchase order
details, time sheets and expenses. The system integrates with CMG's Fact2000
financial and accounting package and with third party software products,
such as Lotus 1-2-3.
Suppliers: CMG Computer Management Group, a UK company owned 96 per cent by
employees: the remainder of investment is by Midland Montagu Ventures.
The company has 1,700 employees of whom 80 per cent own shares; there are
600 employees in UK. Turnover: Pounds 103m with Pounds 9.1 profit in 1991,
Pounds 96m with Pounds 8.6m profit in 1990.
Number of users: one in the UK.
Price: around Pounds 25,000, dependent on user bespoke requirments.
Hardware and operating systems: Open Systems, Unix sales and
support/maintenance: exclusively through CMG. Other services include
implementation consultancy, bespoke development and facilities management.
Contact: Andy McCallum, Computer Management group, Astronaut House, Hounslow
Road, Feltham; tel 081.844 1080.
</TEXT>
