<PROFILE>_AN-DCKCYAGDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930311
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1993 (3): Flying in tight
formation - Air Fleet application
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AT a time when many airlines are shrinking, Britannia, the biggest charter
airline in the world, is taking on a new fleet. The project of commissioning
new aircraft involves every aspect of the company's operations: engineering,
flight operations, catering, cabin services, and training.
It was the need to involve so many people in many different tasks that
triggered off the acquisition of a PC-based project management system,
Hoskyns PMW (Project Manager Workbench).
Capt Paul Watson, fleet captain of both the 757 and 767 Airbuses, was
designated project manager, somewhat to his own surprise, as he had no
project management background. He is a working pilot, whose tasks include
flying the new aircraft back from Seattle. With the help of Hoskyns - which
was already working at Britannia on its strategic CORE system for crew and
aircraft planning - Capt Watson decided on a PC-based solution late in 1990
to help him co-ordinate the resources.
His project was to the introduction of an entire fleet over three years. By
summer 1994, Britannia will have 14 new 757 Airbuses. The company caters for
the charter package holiday market, which has continued to expand even
during the recession: Britannia made profits of Pounds 28.7m on a turnover
of Pounds 471.9m in 1991.
The 757 and 767 models are so similar in cockpit design that some of the
tasks can be duplicated for the introduction of both. But back in 1990, the
commissioning of the very first five 757s was done within a very tight
nine-month timescale. The craft had to be in operation by summer 1991, and
that affected everyone in the whole airline.
To meet the deadline, Capt Watson first marshalled his resources, and the
first step was to sit down with a Hoskyns project management consultant, to
do a 'project definition.'
'I found this an interesting exercise, as it is in the very nature of our
business to use highly disciplined techniques. Good safety is good business
for us, and with high capital investment, you must be able to analyse why
you are doing something, how you are doing it, who needs to be involved, and
how much it is going to cost.
'Where PMW came in was in deciding what degree of control you need,' says
Capt Watson.
In the early phases, choosing the exact specification from the 3 ins-thick
book of options was a complex task. In providing its 'Royal Class' service
in long and short-haul flights, Britannia needs a high standard in such
things as the cabin-trim: handicap-assist rails and nappy-changing
facilities in the lavatories, video entertainment for all passengers, and a
galley to support hot-food service.
'The complete exercise touched everyone in the airline, and we had to have
the specification definition done by the right time, which meant everyone
had to feed back their requirements,' explains Capt. Watson.
He put together a team of eight people, middle managers in flight
operations, engineering, customer services, ground operations, pilot
training, liaison and finance, helped by the Hoskyns project management
consultant. Although he did not use many of the traditional PM techniques
apart from Gantt charts (a way of showing project activities as bars on a
time chart),the PMW software gave Capt Watson 'the big picture.'
'If I could turn the clock back, I would have used critical-path analysis:
it would have been time well spent, although then, it seemed that we didn't
have the time to invest in the learning curve,' he comments. Nevertheless,
the Gantt chart produced at every meeting focused people's minds.
'A visible piece of paper was the focus of attention. It helped us keep
project meetings short and to the point, made sure that we didn't get
sidetracked and spend hours on things that could be sorted out by a couple
of individual team members outside the meeting.
'Within hours I'd update the activity plan and certainly by the next working
day, people had the next week's Gantt chart.'
Although PMW remains 'in the toolkit,' it is no longer in active use, and
the project management role, following the 1990-91 rush, has passed into
other hands. By contrast the team itself has remained in place, because it
proved to be such a useful mechanism for dealing with other issues that
arose, such as re-organising seating plans.
'I know that I can pick up the phone and get something dealt with by the
right person,' explains Capt Watson. 'It gives me a high degree of
confidence that things will get done the way I want them to be, because we
all talk the same language.'
*****
SOFTWARE DETAILS
Project Manager Workbench
PMW was developed by Applied Business Technology. Hoskyns launched a Windows
version of PMW in January 1993: the DOS version has been available since
1991. PMW includes powerful planning, resource scheduling, tracking and
control features.
PMW for Windows allows users to produce different views of a project which
can be customised to display data in formats that meet pr ecise informatin
needs of all those inolves in the project management process.
Companion products: Risk and Bridge, are available specifically for managing
risk and resourcing in IT projects.
Suppliers: Hoskyns Group was founded in 1964, and is now majority owned by
French IT company Cap Gemeni Sogeti, one of the largest computer services
companies in the world. Turnover: Pounds 197.7m, with profits of Pounds 12m,
(1992).
Employees: 3,300 worldwide.
Price: Pounds 1,250 plus VAT for DOS and Windows versions.
Hardware and operating systems: IBM compatible PCs (640K), Windows 3.0.
Sales and support/ maintenance: sold direct through Hoskyns, with support
via client support programme, available at Pounds 250 a year. The support
programme includes access to Helpdesk for technical queries, free updates,
and user group. Training, consultancy and large project planning service
available.
User views: pros - 'PC-based, expert consultancy on hand, disciplined
approach, standard product suited to the IT industry.' Cons: 'Not widely
applicable outside IT.'
Contact: Hoskyns Project Systems Division, Hoskyns PLC, 95 Wandsworth Road,
London SW8 2LX Tel 071 735 0800.
</TEXT>
