<PROFILE>_AN-DCKCYAGBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930311
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1993 (2): Every project
tells a story - By failing to plan, many managers are planning to fail / A
look at the importance of project management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EVERY PROJECT, like a story, has a beginning, a middle, and an end. Geoff
Reiss, in his entertaining book, Project Management Demystified, gives a
simple definition: 'A project is a human activity that achieves a clear
objective against a time scale.'
According to Jim Mackay, the large projects adviser at CMG, there are three
common ingredients to every project: its transient nature, the need to build
and motivate a team, and the fact that at the end of the day, that team will
be disbanded.
'Project management is by definition concerned with the management of
change,' he says. 'Any project needs to balance three elements: time-scales,
cost and quality: these could apply to anything from building the channel
tunnel to mounting a play.'
The Project Managers' Association, set up 25 years ago, grew from the
construction industry, which now only accounts for 40 per cent of its
members: another 40 per cent are in information technology (IT). The group
is working on a certification process for project managers.
The publication, Project Management Today, which regularly reviews software
packages in depth, suggests a broader scope, with readers in IT, finance,
pharmaceuticals, food, and aerospace, as well as civil engineering. The
scope of project management (PM) packages is widening in tune with this
development. According to the US Software Publishing Association, there was
a 63 per cent growth in PM software sales 1991-92.
At a time when computer shows are failing, 'Project Management 93,' (March
23-24), has increased its floorspace at the Novotel, Hammersmith. As the
following selection of stories shows, there is a wide variety of
applications, and at the lower PC and Mac end of the marketplace, user
friendliness is more important than some traditional PM features. Tony
Brady, program manager for Microsoft's Project (see Oxford Training story,
page 10) had the job of 'localising' Project for worldwide use. Project is
thought to have about half the PC PM marketplace, and 70 per cent of
Windows-based market.
Tony Brady sees the typical Project user as a mid-range professional with
100-200 tasks to manage - 'Some people do use it daily, but the tremendous
growth potential is in helping people who need something occasionally to
help plan their work.'
For that reason Brady concentrated on integrating Project with other
applications, such as electronic mail, and on making it user friendly.
It is surprising how few companies interviewed used electronic mail or
'groupware' as an integral part of their communications. Clive Holtham,
professor of Information Management at the City University Business School
and author of a report on workgroups, sees this area as a threat to
traditional vendors.
'The emerging generation of groupware applications could threaten them,
because it's a better overall fit to the complex business of project
management.'
'Attack the risks before they attack you,' sums up the motivation for most
people using PM packages. But consultant Noel Eden has developed a
non-computerised project management, called Risk Analysis Methodology.
Packages, he says, are not always the answer because they do not adapt to
experience. Geoff Reiss, who is directing a series of seminars at the PM 93
exhibition, hopes to convince senior managers of the need to use scheduling
techniques - 'by failing to plan, so many of them are planning to fail,' he
says.
References:
Project Management Demystified by Geoff Reiss; E&amp;FN Spon, 1992; includes a
list of 40 PM software packages.
Project Manager Today: Ken Lane, tel. 0734 761944.
Project Management 93 Exhibition, March 23-24; tel Richard White, 0256
762460.
Noel Eden, tel. 0904 762653.
Quality Forum, Gatwick Gordon Irvine, tel. 0895 635222.
The following is a list of project management buzzwords:
Project management (PM) software is used to schedule resources to achieve an
objective within set time-scales, quality, and cost. Graphics are an
important element in showing members of the team their responsibilities and
how they interact with others.
Gantt charts: originated by Henri Gantt in France at the start of the
century, the Gantt chart provides a pictorial representation of the start
and finish of various activities on a project and how they overlap.
'Gantts,' as they are called, do not show specific dependencies, but they
provide a framework for timescale.
Network diagram, on the other hand is a generic term encompassing critical
path analysis, Pert, (project evaluation and review technique), and critical
path method logic. A network diagram shows main activities and dependencies,
although not necessarily on a timescale.
There are two main methods: activity on arrow, (connecting nodes which
denote events) and precedence, using boxes to denote activities and arrows
to denote dependencies. The resource profile estimates resources plotted to
a timescale.
Critical path analysis - cpa - defines those activities which if delayed,
cause a knock-on effect, delaying the entire project. Others not on the
critical path carry some 'float' or 'slack' meaning that they can be started
later without impacting the overall timescale. For example, the critical
path for office block is design and installation of lifts; in aircraft
design it's the undercarriage.
Auto-scheduling allows the software-users to take all activities and
resources and automatically plot them on a timescale to produce a Gantt
chart, defining start and end dates. (A dangerous facility in which to place
too much faith, say some).
Time collection: a process of collecting and analysing time-sheets for
accurate project control (monitoring of progress) and cost-control. The
process can be speeded by networking and 'forms' facilities, either on paper
or via electronic mail. It is often integrated with accounting to bill for
the work, translating effort into cost.
Risk management - there are qualitative and quantitive methods for analysis
and management of risks in projects, such as the use of unfamiliar
technology.
This is usually part of an integrated quality plan.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XAZ  World.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7372 Prepackaged Software.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
</DOC>
