<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1993 (1): Why software is
over-priced - Alan Cane examines the reasons why European software buyers
are continuing to pay more than users in the US / European Viewpoint
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THAT the cost of computer hardware and software in Europe is high, perhaps
exorbitantly so compared with the US, is not news. It is not even
controversial; in free markets, suppliers are at liberty to charge whatever
price they like and competition is presumed to act as the universal
leveller. What is surprising is the seeming acquiescence of European
customers who, knowing that the prices they are being charged are far higher
than can be accounted for by distribution, insurance and the costs of doing
business in Europe, pay up regardless.
The US magazine Information Week has been at the forefront of a campaign to
expose the cost differentials that exist. Research published in its December
1992 issue suggests that on average buyers in the UK pay about half as much
again for their software as their US competitors; French computer users are
the most exploited paying 1.8 times the US cost of a piece of software. So,
for example, Lotus 1-2-3 selling for Dollars 495 in the US, costs Dollars
752 in the UK, Dollars 821 in Germany and Dollars 1006 in France.
'It is not just mass-market pc software' the magazine observed. 'Enterprise
software, networking software, even Unix software such as the Informix
relational database, are subject to the European premium'.
Does it matter? The lack of any great public agitation about the issue would
suggest computers users simply accept the differential as a fact of business
life. The hard truth, however, that the European software market is
dominated by US suppliers and that the position is unlikely to change much
in the future. Customers who pay too much for their software are putting
themselves at a disadvantage compared to their US competitors.
There are three reasons. First, information technology is accepted as
essential to efficient business but it may cost a company between one and
five per cent of its revenues. Paying over the odds for software simply adds
to the burden.
Second, most companies both here and in the US have some way to go in
learning how best to use their information technology (IT); if software
costs are a barrier to software purchase, the company is giving up a place
on learning curve it may find difficult to reclaim. It is a common complaint
among hardware suppliers that 'intelligent' customers willing to make bold
and imaginative use of IT are scarce in Europe; high software prices are no
incentive for change.
Third, highly priced software increases the temptation to illegally copy
programs. This practice has been widespread in Europe in large and small
companies. It is now being curbed thanks to the efforts of the Business
Software Alliance which has resolutely pursued firms it suspects of
cheating, taking court action where necessary to ensure compliance with the
law.
WHAT is a fair price in Europe for US software ? Whatever the market will
bear, is the cynical response but most buyers and sellers agree the premium
for doing business in Europe should be a surcharge of no more than 10 to 30
per cent of the US price.
Social costs - salaries and benefits - for example, are higher in Europe
than in the US. There are heavy costs associated with translating a product
for each of Europe's diverse national markets which can be equivalent to the
cost of developing a new package from scratch. And there are marketing and
currency exchange costs to be reckoned with. There has been, nevertheless,
tremendous growth in the packaged software market in the past year. The
latest UK figures from the marketing consultancy Romtec suggests that 1992
sales for all packaged applications were 43 per cent up on 1991. Graphics
led the way with 86 per cent growth over 1991, but established applications
like word processing and spreadsheets are still showing growth rates of over
40 per cent.
Some portion of this must be due to customers switching from DOS-based
applications to Microsoft's Windows. Microsoft and Lotus have also
stimulated the market by bundling together several of their most popular
programs in suites selling for a large discount on the sum cost of the
individual programs. Microsoft, for example, sells its Office suite for
Pounds 575; the individual packages, Word, Excel and Powerplus, cost Pounds
395 each if sold separately.
THERE are some sound reasons why European customers seem to be accepting the
situation without a fight. In the first place, analyses like that carried
out by Information Week tend to rely on suppliers' retail list prices.
Street prices may be very different - perhaps as much as 30 per cent to 40
per cent below list.
Second, larger customers have the muscle to strike advantageous deals with
their suppliers - discounts for quantity, multiple-site licences and so on.
Third, even smaller customers can strike worthwhile bargains by shopping
around.
The fact remains, nevertheless, that Europeans are paying too much for their
software. The chief barrier to change seems to be that customers have few or
no levers to exert pressure on suppliers. There are a number of
self-interest groups like the Computer Users of Europe, established to lobby
Brussels and the European Parliament on behalf of customers during a
squabble over software protection last year which seemed to pose a threat to
the open systems movement. It is well aware of the problem but so far is
still considering what approaches would be most appropriate.
The problem may be well on the way to solving itself. The accelerating pace
of globalisation in the computer industry is already creating strong
pressures for a convergence of prices world-wide. In this issue of Software
at Work there are examples of companies including Rockwell Graphics and
British Telecom which are sourcing their project management software
globally.
Companies of this size and market muscle will not be prepared to buy at
different prices in different territories. For the moment, though, unless
Europe's users can organise themselves to bring pressure to bear on
suppliers, they will continue to pay over the odds for their software.
</TEXT>
