<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / World Stock Markets (America): New Dow record after early
fall is reversed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
AFTER running into early profit-taking yesterday, US stock markets regained
their poise thanks to a late surge of buying, which lifted indices to new
highs, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed a net 6.22 up at 3,478.34, a record
and well above its low for the day of 3,449.43. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500
ended 1.93 higher at 456.33, while the American SE composite added 2.86 at
421.88 and the Nasdaq composite firmed 3.91 to 692.87. New York SE trading
volume was 256m shares and rises outnumbered falls by 1,039 to 828.
After reaching record levels during the first two days of the week, stock
prices were hit by concerted selling when the market opened. Traders
reported that an early decline in bond prices triggered the sell-off,
although the likely motive was an eagerness among investors to book some of
the profits earned earlier in the week. Among the selling a number of
sizeable program trades were spotted.
Prices steadily recovered during the afternoon, culminating in a late rush
of buying that pushed stocks into positive territory only in the final 30
minutes of trading.
No important new economic figures were released yesterday, although the
Federal Reserve's 'Beige Book' report on the state of the economy nationwide
showed that business activity continued to pick up in the first two months
of the year, in spite of sluggish loan demand and continued weakness in some
regional economies.
Walt Disney was one of the most heavily traded issues, slipping Dollars  1/2
to Dollars 45 after a seller offloaded at Dollars 44 a large block of shares
 -2.8m in all. There was no indication as to who had sold the stake, or why.
Drug shares were in demand as investors searched for bargains in a sector
which has been hit hard recently by speculation that President Clinton plans
to impose price controls on pharmaceutical products as part of his
healthcare reforms. Merck improved Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 40 in volume of
3.9m shares, Pfizer Dollars 3 1/2 to Dollars 63 1/4 , Schering-Plough
Dollars 2 to Dollars 61 1/2 , Bristol-Myers Squibb Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars
58 1/2 and Glaxo Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 19 7/8 .
News that Primerica is negotiating to buy the Shearson brokerage business
from American Express continued to boost the financial services group's
stock. Primerica was up Dollars 1 7/8 at Dollars 46 5/8 in volume of more
than 1m shares. American Express shed Dollars 3/4 to Dollars 27 1/8 , having
originally risen on news of the proposed deal.
Genesis Health moved ahead Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 14 3/4 after an analyst
at securities house Merrill Lynch raised the firm's short-term rating on the
stock from 'above average' to 'buy' and named the company its pick of the
week.
On the Nasdaq market, Biosurface Technologies plunged Dollars 2 3/8 to
Dollars 6 after the company revealed that it had suspended a clinical trial
of its Anticel product, a dressing used for donor site wounds.
Canada
THE TORONTO market closed narrowly mixed after further heavy trading. The
TSE 300 index was off 1.2 at 3,552.0 but advancing issues led declines by
350 to 321. Volume amounted to 52.5m shares valued at some CDollars 530m.
Eight of the 14 sub-group indices were lower, led by golds, down 1.1 per
cent as the spot price for gold in New York eased 30 cents to a seven-year
low of USDollars 326.55. The media group advanced 1.4 per cent.
