<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Government Bonds: Strong gains in European notes as interest
rates ease
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN bond prices rallied yesterday, buoyed by the Bundesbank's cut in
the variable-rate repo to 8 1/4 per cent, and the easing of interest rates
in the Netherlands, Belgium and Denmark.
German, Dutch and Belgian bonds all ended substantially higher on the day as
dealers returned to speculation about the chances of a two-speed Europe, but
other markets also benefited from the rate easing.
The Bundesbank had announced a cut in its fixed-rate repo to 8 1/4 per cent
on Friday, but dealers were waiting for confirmation yesterday that the new
variable-rate repo would be set in line with the fixed-rate repo.
The move fuelled expectations that a key interest rate reduction will emerge
from the next Bundesbank council meeting, on March 18.
Bund prices rose half a point, after hopes of further easing were sparked by
rate cuts in the Netherlands and Belgium.
THE DUTCH and the Belgian authorities acted in tandem to reduce rates,
following the Bundesbank move, sparking price gains in both bond markets.
Discount rates in both countries were reduced by by  1/4 point to 7 1/4 per
cent.
The Belgian National Bank said the move took into account the recent easing
of German rates and had been facilitated by the strength of the Belgian
franc.
Dutch 10-year bond prices rallied  5/8 point, while 30-year bond prices rose
more than a point, and 10-year Dutch bond yields ended three basis points
below comparable bund yields.
Prices in 10-year Belgian bonds rallied by around  3/8 point following the
rate moves.
THE DANISH bond market rallied strongly yesterday, adding to larger gains
made on Tuesday, when the market soared ahead. The authorities cut interest
rates by half a point yesterday, sparking a rally in the bond market of more
than half a point.
FRENCH government bonds recovered after a weak start to end half a point
higher. However, the tone of the market remains rather nervous in the run up
to the National Assembly elections later this month.
THE GILTS market ended  1/4 point higher yesterday, boosted by news that the
latest Pounds 300m gilt tap had been absorbed by the market. Dealers are now
focusing on next week's Budget, with widespread speculation that this will
include a move to deal with the government's mounting public sector
borrowing requirement.
ITALIAN bond prices recovered somewhat yesterday, after prime minister
Giuliano Amato won a key vote of confidence in the Senate. Prices ended
about  1/4 point higher
THE US bond market traded somewhat erratically yesterday after posting early
gains, although ultimately prices were little changed across the board.
In late trading, the benchmark 30-year government bond was up  1/16 at 104
15/16 , yielding 6.736 per cent. At the short end of the market, the
two-year note was down  1/32 at 99 23/32 , to yield 4.013 per cent.
In the middle of the maturity range, however, prices were slightly weaker
amid reports of selling by the German central bank. The seven-year note was
down  7/32 at 104 1/4 , yielding 5.612 per cent.
Prices at the short and long end of the market opened firmer, aided by
continued defeasance buying by municipal funds, and some short covering by
dealers.
After dropping back soon after midday, prices recovered on reports that the
Senate Budget Committee was looking at a plan to slash issuance of 30-year
bonds by the Treasury. The Treasury secretary, however, later said there
would be no dramatic change in the debt mix, and prices eased off their
highs.
</TEXT>
