<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / International Company News: Unilever set to exploit Rao's
liberalisations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL and R C MURTHY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HINDUSTAN Lever, the Indian affiliate of the Anglo-Dutch combine Unilever,
is taking control of Tata Oil Mills Company (Tomco), a member of Tata,
India's largest industrial grouping. It is one of the country's largest
corporate deals.
The companies describe the move as a merger, but management of the combined
group will rest with Hindustan Lever, a local market leader in soaps and
detergents in which Unilever holds a 51 per cent stake.
The deal will permit Lever to bolster its position as it faces growing
competition from multinationals entering the Indian market in the wake of
the economic liberalisation out by Mr P. V. Narasimha Rao, the prime
minister. Last December, Godrej, another leading local group, signed a joint
venture with Proctor and Gamble, Unilever's international rival.
.Mr Ratan Tata, chairman of Tata Sons, the group's central company, believes
Tata needs to focus on core businesses such as steel, vehicles, chemicals
and computers.
</TEXT>
