<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Major braced for further Maastricht defeats
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, RALPH ATKINS and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is braced for as many as five further defeats on Labour
amendments to the Maastricht bill in the wake of Monday's setback, a cabinet
minister conceded yesterday.
Although none of the amendments would halt British ratification of the
treaty, they would undoubtedly undermine further the government's authority
and sap morale among loyalist pro-Maastricht MPs.
Amid fresh Conservative party rows over Maastricht following Monday's
defeat, when Labour, Liberal Democrat and Tory rebels scored a 22-vote
victory over the government, the minister said: 'The ship can take on some
water. So long as it stays on course, that is what matters.'
The 'Positive Europeans' group of Tory MPs last night wrote to the chairman
of the party's backbench 1922 committee complaining about executive members
who have voted against the government.
However, Mr John Major has taken a strategic decision not to antagonise Tory
Euro-rebels, believing many are fighting over what they see as genuine
points of principle. He is anxious to maintain Conservative unity in the
long term, not least in nine months' time when the Maastricht legislation
should be passed.
Amid chaotic scenes, Labour MPs disrupted Commons' business last night with
procedural votes in pre-emptive retaliation against the threat of the
government trying to extend today's resumed debate on Maastricht into Friday
or beyond. Labour has said that all its MPs will remain at Westminster if
proceedings do continue into the weekend, even at the expense of the party's
Scottish conference in Inverness.
Ministers, who are playing down the significance of Monday's vote, appear
ready to leave the arm-twisting of Tory rebels to loyalist backbench
colleagues who are expected to resume their criticisms at a 1922 committee
meeting today.
In practice, surveys of Conservative constituency association chairmen -
showing many supportive of the rebels - reveal there is little the prime
minister can do to contain the revolt.
Leaders of the Euro-sceptics were unbowed yesterday, saying they could
support at least some of Labour's amendments, including one on the social
chapter. Although there is evidence of some splits among the rebels, tactics
are also being kept secret.
The government's vulnerability has, meanwhile, markedly raised morale on the
Labour benches, following its victory on Monday. But Mr John Smith, the
Labour party leader, yesterday made clear that the opposition would do
nothing to prevent eventual ratification of the accord.
Battle for the 'franc fort', Page 22
</TEXT>
