<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Observer: Con jobs
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
High unemployment is evidently proving good business for some, and on an
international scale. Witness, for example, the 30 would-be workers from
South Africa marooned in Bahrain.
Having been offered lucrative locally advertised oil-rig jobs in Kuwait with
'Offshore International', they each handed the supposed company's agent
nearly Pounds 5,000 for travel costs and a 'character premium' to ensure
they would serve for a given time.
The organiser travelled with them part-way, promising that a courier would
be waiting in Bahrain to take them to the site. When he failed to
materialise, they checked and discovered there was no such company, and of
course no jobs.
But the con artist responsible, who had an Australian accent and claimed
Irish origins, seems unlikely to be the same conman wanted for interview by
the British police. Styling himself D A Baxter, he has been purporting to
recruit sales staff for Euro Disney, asking applicants for advance payments
to cover costs.
With convincingly English restraint, however, he is charging only Pounds
6.75 a head.
</TEXT>
