FT  11 MAR 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Are crabs turning into land animals? Wildlife On One (8.00 BBC1) considers
how so many of these creatures in the last 35m years - scarcely more than a
flash in the evolutionary pan - have been leaving the water and adapting to
life on land. Close To Home (8.30 C4) considers the development in Britain
of American style lobbying groups such as Bristol's COGB, mainly a church
group. Local MP William Waldegrave initially supported them but now says the
group is in danger of setting itself up as a rival to the democratic
structure. Tim Hunkin passes an electric current through the carbon core of
a pencil until it gets red hot and the wood burns off, then puts it inside a
milk bottle and pumps out the air to make a DIY light bulb in his series The
Secret Life Of ..(8.30). Another impressive series is A Labour Of Love on
BBC2 (9.30) which describes the treatment of babies and children in the
first half of the 20th century. Continuing its undercover approach to
journalism, Disguises infiltrates a time-share company (9.30 ITV). Harry
Enfield's Guide To Opera tries to explain 'why all opera plots are bonkers'
(10.30 C4).
