<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Patients' complaint system
criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NATIONAL Health Service's system for handling complaints is attracting
growing criticism, Mr William Reid, health service commissioner, told MPs
yesterday.
Mr Reid said nearly a fifth of patients' complaints investigated in the
1991-1992 financial year by the commissioner's team, which acts as an
National Health Service watchdog, were about the service's procedure for
complaints. Three quarters were upheld as valid.
The total volume of complaints about the health service rose by 19 per cent
in the 1991-1992 year, to 1,176 - the highest since the post of health
commissioner was created.
Although these cases predated the introduction of the government's patients'
charter, which cited the improvement of the complaints procedure as one of
its goals, Mr Reid said he was continuing to receive criticism about the new
complaints system as well.
Patients have said staff were rude or unhelpful, and that their inquiries
had circulated back and forth between different offices, Mr Reid said.
Sir Duncan Nichol, chief executive of the NHS, insisted that measures were
being taken to train medical staff to be more sympathetic and effective in
dealing with complaints. Sir Duncan said: 'We are talking about changing
attitudes and the culture of the system.' He admitted that in this respect
the NHS 'still had a long way to go'.
He added: 'I do not see there is a flaw in the system, but people are not
operating the system to the standards that I wish.'
Although the NHS is planning a league table showing how health authorities
matched up to some aspects of the patients charter, their handling of
complaints would not be compared in this way, Sir Duncan said.
</TEXT>
