FT  11 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Gould warns of opposition to treaty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GROWING opposition by Labour backbenchers to the Maastricht treaty was
forecast yesterday by Mr Bryan Gould, one of its leading opponents, Ivor
Owen writes. He was an unsuccessful challenger to Mr John Smith for the
party leadership.
He warned that if the treaty were ratified it would lead to permanently
entrenched deflation.
Mr Gould recalled that more than 60 Labour MPs joined Conservative
Euro-sceptics and MPs from minority parties in voting against the government
last May. He predicted that many Labour MPs would vote against the third
reading.
Mr Gould told a parliamentary press gallery lunch that if the treaty were to
be enforced there would be no escape route from handing over to unelected
bankers all the key decisions about economic policy.
Mr Gould maintained that for Labour to support the treaty would mean the
party abandoning its principles.
