<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Contracts for civil servants
questioned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INTRODUCTION of fixed-term contracts for senior civil servants was
unlikely to improve the quality of advice given to ministers, Sir Robin
Butler, head of the Civil Service, told a committee of MPs last night.
A switch to such contracts has been recommended by the European Policy
Forum, an influential free-market think-tank, following concern about the
quality of policy advice given to ministers.
Sir Robin told the all-party Treasury and Civil Service committee that civil
servants were less likely to give 'frank and fearless' advice if they were
employed under fixed-term contracts.
'Advice to ministers is more likely to be impartial if advisers do not see
the end of a fixed-term contract approaching,' he said. 'A willingness to
tell ministers that a particular action is wrong is encouraged by security
of tenure.'
Sir Robin rejected suggestions that standards of Civil Service behaviour had
declined in recent years.
He was concerned about public unease over the role of civil servants in
cases such as the sale of arms to Iraq revealed by the Matrix Churchill
trial and the payment of certain expenses on behalf of Mr Norman Lamont, the
chancellor.
But the particular cases were very different and he did not think they
indicated anything was wrong.
Sir Robin accepted that questions of Civil Service impartiality were bound
to be raised when one party had been in power for so long.
He said: 'Scepticism arises about whether the Civil Service is able to serve
a government of another party with equal commitment. I believe that it
could, and all civil servants were concerned to demonstrate that they could
in the run-up to the last election.'
</TEXT>
