FT  11 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Clarke rebuffs Blair on terrorism
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR's call for talks with the government aimed at re-establishing a
bi-partisan approach to terrorism in Northern Ireland and mainland Britain
was dismissed as a 'smokescreen' by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the home secretary,
in the Commons last night.
Following his lead, Tory backbenchers repeatedly attacked Mr Tony Blair,
shadow home secretary, accusing him of giving encouragement to terrorism
while criticising the government for not being tough enough in dealing with
the general crime wave.
Mr Clarke insisted there could be no justification for Labour MPs holding to
the course they adopted in 1983 by voting against the annual order renewing
the Prevention of Terrorism Act introduced by the last Labour government.
At one point Mr Blair complained of 'barracking' by Tory MPs as he argued
that independent advisers had recognised that there were fundamental
objections to continuing the home secretary's powers to make orders
excluding terrorist suspects from mainland Britain.
Mr Blair also said there was widespread support for the view that a judge,
and not the home secretary, should decide whether terrorist suspects could
be detained by the police without any charge being made for more than four
days.
The Order to continue the Act's provisions for another year was approved by
329 to 202, a government majority of 127.
