<DATE>930311
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Political Notebook: At risk of sudden death
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR Mr Norman Lamont next Tuesday's Budget is a sudden-death affair. If it
flops, the calls for a new chancellor will become deafening. Mr Lamont will
be gone from the Treasury by the summer recess.
A well judged and well received package would not guarantee his position -
those close to Mr John Major insist he will not make up his mind until the
summer. But with the prime minister weakened by the corrosive conflict over
Maastricht Mr Lamont would have a fighting chance of holding on.
It is an unenviable position for the chancellor, and is made no easier by
the uncertainty which still surrounds the economy's emergence from
recession.
The prevailing view in the cabinet - shared incidentally by Mr Major - is
that recovery is already under way. The drastic loosening in monetary policy
since September's ERM debacle should deliver a significant boost to demand
and incomes. Sterling's devaluation has given exporters a competitive edge
in overseas markets. The US economy is growing strongly. The housing market
shows signs of long-forgotten stability.
But if it is rare now to find a cabinet minister who is anything but upbeat
in private conversation, it is equally difficult to find one who is willing
to be anything like as optimistic in public.
No one is sure whether the recovery they believe is happening has more than
shallow roots. No one quite knows what will be the impact of a slide into
deeper recession in the rest of Europe. Unemployment casts a long and dark
shadow. No one is inclined to be caught out by another false dawn.
So the temptation for Mr Lamont is to do very little next Tuesday, to
announce a distinctly modest increase in personal taxation and spend the
money on a few eye-catching measures to help industry and cut the dole
queues. Fiscal rectitude can be promised for a future occasion.
In the judgment of most of his cabinet colleagues that would be a bad
mistake for Mr Lamont, for the economy, and for the government's authority.
In spite of their concern about the fragility of recovery there has been a
decisive shift in the Lord Howe, the author of the austerity budget which
marked the end in 1981 of an earlier recession, caught the flavour with his
call in the Financial Times this week for a radical reform of the tax system
to generate new revenues. Mr Lamont should choose virtue over instant
popularity.
The chancellor should not despair. Adversity brings its own opportunities.
It is true that the FT's survey of pre-Budget opinion on the Tory back
benches underlines his personal vulnerability. Nearly two thirds of Tory MPs
judge his performance to be no better than fair or disappointing. In a
comparable survey last year that figure was less than 40 per cent.
But the survey underlines also their willingness to swallow some bitter
pills.
If Mr Lamont can project a coherent medium-term programme to get the
government out of its present fiscal mess then Tory MPs will accept an
austerity Budget.
More than half actively support tax increases of one sort or another as part
of a strategy to reduce the deficit. About half that number believe Mr
Lamont must make a substantial down payment next week.
Even those who would prefer him not to renege on the Conservatives' election
pledges to reduce personal taxation appear ready now to accept some discreet
increases.
Not, of course, rises in income tax rates. Only a few brave souls suggest he
should tamper with those. But more that half are willing to see Mr Lamont
reduce the amount homeowners receive through mortgage interest relief. Not
so long ago a threat to that particular tax distortion would have provoked a
revolt of Maastricht proportions.
Similar numbers are ready to see VAT extended to domestic fuel - dressed up,
of course, as a 'green' tax - and to newspapers. They will acquiesce if Mr
Lamont decides against indexing income tax allowances. Most are braced for
much higher fuel - 'green' again - tobacco, and alcohol duties.
The price the backbenchers are demanding is small. They want incentives to
restore industrial confidence - through improved capital allowances and
special measures to help small businesses. About half would like a
post-Budget cut in interest rates - the rest still worry about the exchange
rate.
They want a renewed squeeze on public spending in the summer. But above all
else the government's supporters want a signal that the chancellor has
recovered his grip.
