<DATE>930311
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Guiding light for mandarins: The recession has failed to
hurt one of the Treasury's industrial advisers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TREASURY must wish all its economic advisers had the characteristics of
Mr Ivan Bradbury.
For Mr Bradbury - owner and chairman of fast-expanding electronics company
Interconnection Systems - the recession has never happened.
The physicist-turned-entrepreneur is a member of the Treasury's industrial
prospects committee, which meets quarterly.
He reckons succeeding in business is a matter of following simple rules:
investing in technology and people, close contact with customers and
treating exports in the same way as domestic sales.
Since Mr Bradbury set up his Pounds 37m-turnover company eight years ago
staff has doubled to just over 600 and the business has become consistently
profitable.
Interconnection Systems' progress has been all the more noticeable given
that it is based in South Shields, Tyneside - mainland Britain's biggest
unemployment blackspot, where one worker in five is without a job. A
business associate says of the 46-year-old Mr Bradbury: 'Much of the success
is down to him. He can be a difficult character, but he's bloody intelligent
and prepared to work exceptionally hard.'
Mr Bradbury is probably the least known but best paid member of the Treasury
committee, which was set up last year as part of a government drive to
improve links with manufacturers. The committee reports to Mr Alan Budd,
Treasury chief economic adviser. In the financial year to the end of last
April Mr Bradbury's earnings came to Pounds 333,000.
He thinks the Treasury initiative 'commendable', likening Treasury officials
to pilots flying with the windows blacked out. Although on the whole he
thinks the officials are 'very bright', he says that 'every now and again
they need glimpses of what is happening in the world outside'.
Mr Bradbury, whose previous jobs have included spells at the Ford car group
and US electronics company Raychem, came into contact with Treasury
officials after a meeting in the late 1970s with Sir Douglas Wass, Treasury
permanent secretary between 1974 and 1983. Sir Douglas recalls: 'I was very
impressed with Mr Bradbury. I learned a lot from him (about industry).'
In spite of his close ties with the Treasury, Mr Bradbury criticises
government economic policies for a 'lack of clear sets of values' in
economic management. He says the government 'stopped the economy dead in its
tracks' with the long period of high interest rates in the early 1990s.
Since then it has failed to do enough to help manufacturing growth, but has
relied on a 'simplistic' formula of trying to reduce inflation.
Following recent cuts in interest rates and signs that the economy may be on
the turn, Mr Bradbury is generally confident about recovery. Manufacturers
which cannot step up exports after the 15 per cent devaluation in the pound
since last September 'probably should not be trying'.
He urges the government not to jeopardise an upturn by raising taxes in next
week's Budget. 'At the moment people want to hear good news. The negative
impact of a tax increase would be considerable,' he says.
Interconnection Systems' main activity is making printed circuit boards  -
building blocks for a range of electronic products including telephones,
computers and automotive systems. Mr Bradbury owns 80 per cent of
Interconnection Systems through a holding company called Legibus, with
Schroder Ventures, an investment group, holding the rest of the shares.
The factory operates 24 hours a day and makes about 9m boards a year, nearly
half of them for export. Its customers include Mitsubishi, Daimler-Benz, BMW
and Motorola.
After buying the then lossing-making South Shields factory from the Plessey
electrical group in 1985, Mr Bradbury changed the management and invested
Pounds 25m in new automated machines.
In the financial year ending last April his company turned in a pre-tax
profit of Pounds 2.3m on sales of Pounds 31m. Profits are expected to be
about Pounds 3m this year.
</TEXT>
