<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Education drive urged on business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN PATTEN, the education secretary, yesterday urged business executives
to become more involved in education to ensure that young people leaving
schools and colleges had the skills employers needed.
Mr Patten said at a CBI conference in London that business was being given
more information about school performance through league tables on
examination results.
Employers who were unhappy about the standards of education of
school-leavers should take it up with the schools concerned.
'As a business customer you would not stand on the sidelines and make
general statements about the performance of your suppliers,' he said. 'You
would do something about it.'
Mr Patten said businesses had increasing opportunities to become involved in
education, through governing bodies, education-business partnerships and
Training and Enterprise Councils.
Mr Howard Davies, director-general of the CBI, said at the same conference
said school league tables should be compiled by an independent body such as
the Audit Commission or Ofsted, the new schools inspectorate.
