<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Ford workers 'in battle for sheer survival': Robert Taylor
is told about job fears at Dagenham
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MOOD earlier this week among car workers at a branch meeting of the
Amalgamated Engineering and Electrical Union across the road from Ford Motor
Company's paint, trim and assembly plant in Dagenham was both angry and
anxious.
'There is a lot of fear in the plant,' said one. 'Nobody feels safe.'
Another added: 'It's getting very brutal in there. Workers are being
fingered and told they are going to lose their jobs whether they like it or
not.'
Whether this truly reflects what the majority of workers think about the
company's threat of sackings if voluntary redundancy targets are not met may
be questionable. Ford wants 560 production workers out of 7,500 at Dagenham
to go and it is believed to be half way to that figure.
Some workers, however, see Ford's threat as the thin end of the wedge.
'We are in a battle for sheer survival,' explained one electrician over a
pint in the Mill House social club after the union meeting. 'The very future
of Dagenham is at stake. For every job in the plant there are another three
outside dependent on the company.'
Ford's sprawling complex in east London once enjoyed a reputation for
industrial militancy.
In the 1950s and 1960s it became a byword for unofficial strikes, tough shop
stewards and wage-push inflation among the emerging affluent working class.
It inflicted the last Labour government's first defeat in the 1978-1979
'winter of discontent', when Ford workers burst through the 5 per cent
incomes policy.
Now workers are very much on the defensive. 'We feel we have been pushed
around long enough,' said one maintenance worker.
'Men are being called off the line and told they're going to have to go,'
added another. 'One bloke I know on a training course was informed he was on
his way out.'
In other plants workers have received individual letters to tell them they
have no future in the company.
But in spite of the outpouring of complaints Ford might get its way.
The company will not disclose the general terms of its voluntary redundancy
scheme but it is telling workers individually they would be better off to
take the money while it is on offer.
Mr Seamus Riley, a 28-year-old electrician from County Galway, has worked
for Ford at Dagenham for nearly 4 1/2 years.
A single man and a shop steward, he does not want to give up his job but has
been told he is on the list of those who will have to go.
Like others he faces an invidious choice. If he agrees to leave before the
end of this month he will receive just over Pounds 6,650 in severance pay.
But he has been told that if he turns it down and is then dismissed he will
receive only Pounds 820 from the state redundancy scheme. 'The company are
not offering me enough and there are no other jobs in this area for
electricians,' he argues, waving his redundancy note.
But for many older workers the choice between cash in the hand now or a
pittance from the state next month may well prove decisive. 'It is bribery
but it has worked in the past,' admitted one local union official.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Ford Motor.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
