<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / OFT weighs extension of credit protection
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OFFICE of Fair Trading is investigating whether small companies should
be given similar protection to that available to the private individual
under the Consumer Credit Act.
The government has asked the office to establish whether small businesses,
as consumers of credit and hire services, are sufficiently protected by the
existing legislation. The move was announced yesterday by Sir Bryan
Carsberg, the director-general of fair trading, at the annual conference of
the Institute of Credit Management in London.
At present sole traders and partnerships are treated in the same way as
private consumers, but limited companies, however small, are excluded.
The Consumer Credit Act requires credit organisations to provide purchasers
with detailed information on the total cost of credit and imposes
restrictions on credit companies repossessing goods if payments are not kept
up.
There was little support from the credit industry for a possible extension
of protection beyond individual consumers. The Finance and Leasing
Association said it would be inappropriate to extend the provisions of the
act to companies because it contains many detailed provisions that would be
unnecessary for the more sophisticated business customer.
Ms Victoria Mitchell, legal secretary of the association, which represents
more than 100 non-bank finance and leasing companies, said: 'The act assumes
a low level of knowledge on the part of the purchaser.'
Far from seeking to extend the act to limited companies, she said, the
association had been lobbying to remove sole traders and partnerships from
its cover. Some forms of credit, such as variable rate hire purchase
agreements, could not be offered to private individuals under the act but
were used by businesses. Extending the act would reduce credit options open
to business, she added.
Giving business users of credit extra protection would need specialist
legislation, which the association said would not be in tune with the
government's desire to reduce the burden of legislation on business.
Barclays Bank said only about 10 per cent of its business customers would be
affected by an extension of credit protection to companies because most were
sole traders or partnerships. Both the granter of the credit and the
customer would have to deal with more paperwork if the legislation were to
be extended, it added.
The OFT study forms part of a general review of credit legislation and
credit industry practices.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
