<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Code on directors' pay 'not followed'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LUCY KELLAWAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONLY 16 of Britain's 100 largest companies meet the code of best practice on
disclosure of directors' pay spelled out last December in the Cadbury
committee report on corporate governance, a study published today shows.
The study by pay specialists Monks Partnership of the most recent annual
reports of FT-SE 100 companies shows that significant changes will be needed
to meet the code when it comes into force in June.
Although the code is voluntary, the study says companies are taking it
seriously and intend to change practices by June. Mr Simon Rodwell, a
director at Monks, said it was in companies' interests to follow the code as
compliance is to become a condition for listing of companies on the Stock
Exchange.
Companies must now disclose the aggregate of all directors' pay, and the
total pay of the chairman and of the highest paid director (when different).
The code requires them to separate out the level of bonus in total
directors' pay and in that of the chairman or highest paid director. They
will also have to explain the basis on which incentive pay is calculated and
disclose details of the committee that sets directors' pay.
The study finds most reluctance in declaring the bonus element in the
chairman's salary, with just 28 per cent complying. Only 46 per cent offered
any explanation for the calculation of bonus pay.
According to the report companies not complying with any of the code's
recommendations in their last annual report include Abbey National, BTR,
Lloyds Bank and Unilever. Companies that complied fully include Boots,
British Telecom, Tesco and TSB.
Disclosing Board Earnings. Monks Partnership, Debden Green, Saffron Walden,
Essex CB11 3LX. Pounds 125.
</TEXT>
