<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Kellogg faces second complaint
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNITED Norwest Co-operatives has become the second retailer to report
Kellogg, the breakfast cereal giant, to the Office of Fair Trading for
cutting off its corn flake supplies.
The move follows a similar complaint to the OFT last week from Shoprite, the
Isle of Man-based discount retailer which has 40 stores in Scotland. Mr
Nigel Griffiths, Labour's consumer affairs spokesman, tabled a Commons
question to Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, asking him
to investigate the Shoprite/Kellogg dispute.
United Norwest Co-operatives, one of the 10 biggest food retailers in
Britain, gave away coupons offering 10p off a 500 gramme packet of corn
flakes in a door-to-door leaflet promotion for its Discount Giant
supermarkets.
That defied a Kellogg letter to the grocery trade in January imposing on
500g packets a minimum price of 96p, since raised to Pounds 1.02.
In retaliation Kellogg has stopped all cornflake supplies - of whatever
packet size - to all the group's stores, including its Normid, Shopping
Giant and Late Shop outlets, where the vouchers could not be used. Attempts
to get alternative supplies from food wholesalers have failed. Mr Robert
Cawley, United Norwest's buying controller, said yesterday: 'They have told
us Kellogg will stop their supplies if they sell to us.'
The Co-op, which before Christmas was selling 500g packets of cornflakes for
as little as 80p, is alleging unfair trading and discrimination. Mr Cawley
said several competitors had been honouring the Co-op's 10p-off-Kellogg's
vouchers to win business, but Kellogg has not stopped their supplies.
Evidence to the OFT includes till receipts from competitors showing that the
discount had been applied to Kellogg's 500g cornflakes.
Although Kellogg gets the same wholesale price, cheap cornflakes in the
shops can distort competition with Kellogg's other cereals, especially when
these are being promoted in national advertising.
Kellogg said yesterday: 'It is unreasonable for retailers to use Kellogg's
brands as loss-leaders in order to build their overall business. With
immediate effect we will discontinue supplies to those retailers or
wholesalers who sell below cost for the purpose of loss-leading.'
</TEXT>
