FT  11 MAR 93 / World Trade News: Czechs to complete Temelin N-plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK BLUM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PRAGUE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE CZECH government yesterday gave the go-ahead for completion of the
controversial Kcs68bn (Pounds 1.6bn) nuclear power plant at Temelin in
southern Bohemia.
The decision will be a relief to Westinghouse Corporation of the US, which
won two tenders to help to rehabilitate the plant. Its completion has been
strongly opposed by local environmental groups and by neighbouring Austria.
More than Kcs25bn has been spent on the plant, with orders for another
Kcs19bn placed for equipment, engineering and construction. Westinghouse
will provide high-quality fuels and upgrade the plant to western standards
with new control systems - two of the recommendations by the International
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) after a study of the plant in 1990.
The original decision to build two Soviet-designed VVER (pressurised water
reactor) units of 1,000MW each was taken in 1977, but the plant was put on
ice after the 1986 disaster at the Chernobyl nuclear power plant in Ukraine.
