<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 93 / Tory MPs signal backing for wider VAT in Budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSERVATIVE MPs have signalled that Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, has a
free hand to extend value added tax, cut mortgage interest relief and freeze
income tax allowances to narrow the yawning gap in the government's
finances.
But an FT survey reveals that the chancellor is under strong pressure from
the government's supporters at Westminster to balance austerity for
consumers in next Tuesday's Budget with measures to boost industrial
confidence and investment.
A large majority of Tory MPs want him to spread the pain of deficit
reduction by imposing fresh cuts in Whitehall spending plans. Around half
want him to sweeten the pill with a post-Budget cut in interest rates.
The survey suggests that while any increase in income tax rates would risk a
backbench revolt, the Tory party is ready to accept a wide range of other
measures to boost the Treasury's revenues.
A favourable reception to the Budget from its own side will be critical if
the government is to begin to restore its battered authority after this
week's defeat on the Maastricht treaty. The row over Europe has left the
government's control over its own supporters weaker than at any time since
the 1970s.
The FT survey, based on written replies from 85 Tory MPs, representing a
third of the government's backbench strength, underlines also the Budget's
crucial importance for Mr Lamont's own reputation. Nearly two-thirds judge
his performance as chancellor as 'fair' or 'disappointing'. Only 6 per cent
say he has done an 'excellent' job.
The survey coincides with a hardening of opinion within the cabinet in
favour of immediate action to reduce the deficit. Mr Douglas Hurd, Mr
Michael Heseltine, Mr Kenneth Clarke and Mr John MacGregor are among senior
ministers supporting a package of tax increases.
Mr Lamont, however, can draw comfort from a widespread recognition among
Conservatives at Westminster that next week's Budget will foreshadow tough
measures to reduce the public sector deficit.
Promoting the recovery, helping industry and tackling unemployment are cited
by an overwhelming majority as the main priority for the Budget package. But
most judge also that the chancellor must get to grips with the borrowing
requirement.
Some 56 per cent of Tory MPs favour higher taxes, with more than half of
those seeking immediate action.
The deficit is deemed sufficiently threatening by 30 per cent for them to
call for tax increases both next week and in the November Budget.
Among the key results of the survey are:
Mortgage interest relief, once sacrosanct, is regarded by 53 per cent as a
target for savings. Nearly two-thirds of Tory MPs want a fresh round of
public spending cuts.
Nine-tenths want special measures to help industry and promote investment.
Risk of sudden death, Page 12
Squaring the circle, Page 23
</TEXT>
