<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / Warning on EC postal plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A TOUGH regulatory regime would be essential to ensure that a universal
European postal service was not exploited by monopoly operators, the
Consumers' Association said yesterday.
A European Community green paper on developing a single market for postal
services has suggested the gradual liberalisation of cross-border and direct
mail services in Europe. Although many services would be open to
competition, some areas of activity could be left to monopolies.
The association said in a response to the proposals that they would require
a regulatory framework to ensure that market power handed to particular
operators 'is not exploited in terms of price, quality, availability and
redress provided'.
An EC suggestion that persistent failure to meet service targets might
result in sanctions against operators - including seeking tenders from
alternative providers or the linking of permitted price rises to quality
targets - was also welcomed by the association.
A survey of UK postal users conducted by the association shows that
customers want to keep the present balance of quality of service and price.
Most, however, would accept the scrapping of the two-tier postal service in
favour of a single class. A majority also had no objection to deliveries
being restricted to one a day.
</TEXT>
