FT  10 MAR 93 / Teachers back tests boycott
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PROSPECT of chaos in schools in England and Wales after Easter grew
yesterday, Robert Taylor writes.
Members of the 190,000-strong National Association of Schoolmasters/Union of
Women Teachers voted overwhelmingly to boycott the assessment and testing
associated with the government's national curriculum.
In a secret ballot, 52,493 (88 per cent) voted in favour of the proposed
boycott and only 7,154 (12 per cent) against in a 57 per cent turnout.
'The members' verdict is a stunning indictment of the government's policies
on testing and assessment,' said NASUWT's general secretary Mr Nigel de
Gruchy. He expects Friday's meeting of the union executive to give the
go-ahead to the boycott.
Baroness Blatch, the education minister, condemned the action as
'unprofessional' saying it would 'damage and disrupt children's education'.
