FT  10 MAR 93 / Aer Lingus executive resigns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Cathal Mullan, chief executive of Aer Lingus, the Irish Republic's
national airline, resigned last night and was replaced by Mr Bernie Cahill,
the state-owned company's chairman, Our Foreign Staff reports.
The appointment of Mr Cahill was announced in a statement in the Dail by
Transport Minister Brian Cowen, who said the government would be prepared to
support 'convincing and visible action' by Mr Cahill to solve Aer Lingus's
problems. He made it clear a large cash injection was out of the question.
Reports earlier yesterday had indicated that Aer Lingus, already facing
losses running into hundreds of millions of pounds, stood to lose around
IPounds 90m (Pounds 91m) this year alone.
Mr Cowen denied reports that a cabinet sub-committee, established to monitor
the Aer Lingus position, and headed by premier Albert Reynolds, had plans to
call in international consultants to advise on the airline's future.
Earlier this year it was reported that Aer Lingus was considering shedding
500 of its 7,000-strong work force as part of a survival plan and seeking
more government cash aid.
