<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / Treaty delay threatens jobs, says PM: Maastricht bill
setback irks EC diplomats; Major to press ahead on ratification
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS, DAVID GARDNER and LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BRUSSELS, STRASBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR yesterday warned Labour and Euro-sceptic Tory MPs that delays
to ratification of the Maastricht treaty would cost British jobs as the
government's defeat on Monday provoked angry recriminations within
Conservative ranks.
The prime minister launched his attack as the government sought to reassure
its European partners that Britain would press ahead with ratification as
swiftly as possible. Mr Major said: 'The treaty is in the national interest
and we will pursue it.' Downing Street shrugged off as 'trivial' the 22-vote
defeat on a Labour amendment but indicated government hopes of completing
Maastricht's parliamentary stages this summer are receding. Ratification is
expected before the parliamentary session ends in the autumn, officials
said.
This provoked a mixture of frustration and resignation in Brussels, with
some European Community diplomats speculating about Mr Major's ability to
deliver ratification. European MPs also expressed dismay over the latest
delay and suggested it signalled a loss of authority on Mr Major's part.
Labour's victory on Monday means a Commons 'report' stage will follow the
current committee stage - injecting a delay of as much as a month.
The government hopes the shock of the defeat will lead to strong pressure
from local constituency associations on the rebels to force them into line.
But initial soundings suggested that most of the hard-line Euro-sceptics had
the tacit support of their associations.
At Westminster, conflict between Conservative rebels and loyalists
intensified, in spite of attempts by senior Tories to concentrate attacks on
opposition parties. Tensions were exacerbated by the deals offered by the
government to Welsh and Scottish nationalists in an unsuccessful attempt to
buy enough votes to head off defeat.
The fevered atmosphere was fuelled by confirmation that Mr Michael Portillo,
chief secretary to the Treasury, had lunched recently with Mr Bryan Gould, a
prominent Labour Euro-sceptic. Colleagues of Mr Portillo, seen as
Thatcherite on Europe, played down the significance of the meeting, saying
the two were old friends.
The next twists on Maastricht are likely to centre on amendments introduced
by Labour on economic and monetary union, due for debate next week, and then
on Maastricht's social chapter, described by Sir Marcus Fox, chairman of the
Tory's backbench 1922 committee, as the 'crunch' point.
In angry Commons exchanges with Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, Mr Major
again said the social chapter would 'choke off foreign investment and
destroy jobs'. But he said 'delay in ratifying the Maastricht treaty would
do exactly the same thing'.
Tory Euro-sceptic MPs, who voted with Labour on Monday, were meeting last
night to discuss tactics. Ministers and officials are not ruling out the
possibility of further defeats.
Labour is pledged not to back 'wrecking amendments' that could stop
ratification - and its MPs are expected to reaffirm that stance at a meeting
today. But there is a grey area over its social chapter amendments which are
aimed at requiring the government to insert the chapter into British
legislation before the treaty is ratified.
In Brussels, one diplomat described Mr Major's latest setback as creating
'frustration bordering on exasperation', adding: 'This is throwing a spanner
in the workings of the whole Community; we're in limbo.'
But, at the same time, diplomats from large member states played down the
significance of what one described as 'a procedural hiccup'.
Some EC states' officials criticised Mr Major for allowing uncertainty to
develop last year after Danish voters' rejection of the treaty, thereby
allowing his opponents to gather strength.
'We have all had difficult political problems to resolve, but they are there
to be confronted,' one diplomat said.
In the European Parliament, Mr Jean-Pierre Cot, Socialist group chairman,
said he was worried about Mr Major's mismanagement of the ratification
process. 'I don't know whether he has control to get Maastricht through.'
Mr Poul Nyrup Rasmussen, the Danish prime minister, said: 'I look forward to
ratification of the treaty from the UK side, in the interest of Denmark and
the rest of Europe.'
Danish premier sees Yes for Maastricht, Page 2
An algebra lesson in Tory subversion, Page 8
Editorial Comment, Page 21
Currencies, Page 37
London stocks, Page 46
