<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow holds its own in spite of
profit-taking
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices were little changed yesterday as investors and dealers
consolidated Monday's record-breaking gains, writes Patrick Harverson in New
York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was 2.70 firmer at 3,472.12.
The index spent the entire session only a few points on either side of
opening values. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 moved in a
similar fashion and ended 0.31 off at 454.40, while the American SE
composite finished 2.29 higher at 419.02 and the Nasdaq composite up 1.73 at
688.96. Trading volume on the New York SE came to 290.7m shares.
Early trading was dominated by profit-taking, as investors sought to book
some of Monday's gains. Yet, in spite of the selling, prices held their own,
an indication of the resilience of the market, which remains supported by
extremely low interest rates, low inflation, and hopes for continued
improvements in corporate profitability.
Prices may also have been aided yesterday by further indications from the
White House that President Clinton is willing to accommodate more spending
cuts in his first budget.
On Monday, reports said that the president would accept an additional
Dollars 55bn in cuts; by yesterday that figure had risen to Dollars 90bn.
Analysts have warned, however, that stock prices could be hit by a
short-term correction over the next week or so. Some remain nervous about
the Dow's record highs, fearing that prices may have risen too far, making
stocks overly expensive in relation to future corporate earnings.
Banks remained in demand as investors bought them in the expectation that
low interest rates will boost bank earnings. BankAmerica climbed Dollars
7/8 to Dollars 53, additionally helped by a ratings upgrade from broking
house PaineWebber, while Citicorp added Dollars 1 at Dollars 28, Wells Fargo
Dollars 3 1/8 at Dollars 108 5/8 and Chemical Dollars 1 at Dollars 42 7/8 .
American Express rose Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 27 7/8 and Primerica jumped
Dollars 4 3/4 to Dollars 44 3/4 after the two groups confirmed that they
were in talks which could lead to Primerica buying the brokerage and asset
management operations of American Express's troubled Shearson Lehman unit.
Safeway moved ahead Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 13 7/8 as investors continued
to respond to Monday's news that Mr Peter Magowan, the food retailer's
chairman, is stepping down as chief executive to run a baseball team in
California.
HJ Heinz declined Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 42 3/8 after the company issued a
profits warning, saying that the wild fluctuations in European currencies
had hurt its bottom line.
Some leading drug stocks were under pressure, with Pfizer Dollars  3/4 lower
at Dollars 59 3/4 and Bristol Myers-Squibb down Dollars  3/4 at Dollars 57
1/8 .
Canada
TORONTO stocks ended on a mixed note after further heavy trading, as a
continued rally among mining shares was offset by a decline among financial
services issues.
The TSE 300 index edged 2.2 higher to 3,553.2 and rises narrowly led falls
by 333 to 308 after volume of 54.2m shares. Ten of 14 stock groups closed
ahead, with mining adding 1.5 per cent.
The stocks of two major companies in the Hees-Edper group rose in spite of
releasing substantially weaker 1992 results. Hees International Bancorp
gained CDollars  3/4 at CDollars 9 1/4 and Brascan 'A' put on CDollars  5/8
at CDollars 11 7/8 .
</TEXT>
