<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / International Company News: Haeco profits rise 21% to
HKDollars 387m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HONG KONG Aircraft Engineering Company (Haeco), a Swire Pacific group
company which holds the monopoly on commercial aircraft maintenance and
engineering in the colony, yesterday posted a 21 per cent rise in net
profits for 1992 to HKDollars 387.9m (USDollars 50m), from HKDollars 320.6m
in 1991.
The profits were struck on a 16 per cent increase in turnover to HKDollars
2bn, from HKDollars 1.8bn.
The company said there had been good use of its airframe maintenance
facilities and increased activity in its overhaul division.
Mr Peter Sutch, chairman, said the volume of work passing through Haeco was
expected to be satisfactory during 1993.
To maintain competitiveness, the company was focusing on improvements in
productivity and a drive to improve quality, he said.
These measures were expected to produce an acceptable result in 1993,
despite high inflation in Hong Kong.
Haeco is 51.85 per cent owned by Swire Pacific and 25.04 per cent owned by
Cathay Pacific, the main customer for its services.
